   RH bending angle are used as indicators of significant vertical
   refractivity gradients that often occur on top of the atmospheric
   boundary layer (ABL), convective cloud layers such as the trade-wind
   inversion, and other moist layers in the free troposphere. RH amplitude
   fluctuations are used as an indicator of turbulence in the moist
   troposphere. The approaches are demonstrated using RO data from the
   Constellation Observing System for Meteorology, Ionosphere and Climate
   (COSMIC) mission from September 2006. The global distributions of the
   ABL depths and tops of moist convective layers derived from COSMIC RO
   data correspond generally to the observed locations and structures of
   the Intertropical Convergence Zone and adjacent sub-tropical regions.
   The approaches are suitable for investigations of the temporal and
   spatial ABL variability.}},
